text: Sorry to burst everyone's bubble but Peter is most likely not Pete Wisdom, here is why...  First of all, that idea originally came from one Nerdist article/video written right after the trailer came out. The writer did it to get hits knowing people would google the Peter character; he was obviously reaching. I say this because the only tenuous link he drew that Peter could be Pete Wisdom was that the character's twitter handle is "Pete W.". Because Peter is absolutely nothing like Pete Wisdom in look, mannerisms or personality, occam's razor posits that it is probably either a small coincidence or a deliberate setup to create a little extra buzz (which, if it was, worked excellently). Either way it most likely means nothing.  It seems much more plausible that Peter is just a stand in character for Deadpool's usual sidekick "Hydra" Bob (the mook Deadpool recognized, chatted up and then promptly knocked out during the scrapyard fight in the first film [Which i'm sure will happen again in some variation in the sequel as well as a kind of running gag]). Since Bob is a "knockaround guy" kind of sidekick in a few runs of the comics they probably decided to flip the script on that iteration of the character and make him an average dude (with a likewise average name) who isn't superpowered or a secret agent or anything for Deadpool to mine for juxtapositional comedy. That way he also becomes a surrogate for the audience so he probably won't end up a bad guy or get hurt. More likely that he will come out unscathed and a hero after some close calls and/or he will be actively ignored by enemies to comedic effect. Plus the actor who plays Peter (Rob Delaney) is hilarious so better to make him "one of the team" so to speak.  Thanks in advance to anyone who takes the time to read such an in-depth analysis of something so trivial lol

text: Deadpool 2 is receiving huge praise in the form of extremely high scores among test screening audiences.  The Fox sequel, released in May, is reportedly receiving marks as high as 98 following two previous screenings' scores of 91 and 97, respectively.  This is higher than the first Deadpool which saw the hugely-popular blockbuster receive a mark of 91 ahead of its release in 2016. The film - which starred Ryan Reynolds in the lead role - went on to gross $783m (£684m) globally.  Test screenings of films ask recruited audience members to rate different versions of films using boxes marked excellent, very good, good, fair, and poor.    Crew members attended the final test screenings with one audience member describing the atmosphere to the Super Bowl.  Deadpool 2 underwent reshoots following its previous two test screenings with reports revealing a secret cameo was added.   The sequel sees Josh Brolin play the villainous role of Cable alongside newcomers with Zazie Beetz (Domino) and Julian Dennison. Morena Baccarin, T.J. Miller, Stefan Kapicic and Brianna Hildebrand will all return.  The Hollywood Reporter states the final test, which took place in Dallas, showcased two separate cuts simultaneously, one receiving 94 and the other 98; Fox will reportedly release the latter cut. text: Saw it today, pretty good. First forty ish minutes were a bit miserable and bleak for Deadpool standards. It does pick itself up though. Cable is a great villain and Domino is decent. I wish there was more time spent with Colossus, Negasonic and Negasonics new japanese girlfriend. That character has around a minute of time on screen throughout the whole film and I wanted to see her do more than just deliver punch lines. The kid was fine, I thought id find him annoying but at least he is an annoying character with a bit of depth and substance. Action scenes aren't as smooth as Deadpool 1 but there is a very impressive fight scene near the end featuring Colossus. Whearas Deadpool 1 was clear cut 'I find the guy that ruined my life and make him make it better'. Deadpool 2 is 'because of this incident I find myself doing this and ending up here which causes this and I have to leave to go here until I get here and meet these characters and we all go here' you get the point. The plot is more complex but it isn't necessarily a bad change, just one that I wasn't expecting. Humour was never enough to make me laugh but I was grinning a lot. There is a scene on a couch in the blind ladys  living room that had the audience behind me crying with laughter whilst screaming 'NOOO'. Final thing I have to mention is the after credits scene as its one of the best parts of the movie. It's... So... Good, just stay and watch it... Please. It was easily the funniest part of the movie if you can understand where it stems from.

text: Quick update for all of those who went to see the R Rated Version of Deadpool 2 & are waiting on the R Rated Release fir home formats & if the story I've read is to believed & is in fact true then I won't be buying it on DVD & Blu Ray unless the Kids version is there as an option...  It seems that the writers of Deadpool 2 Rhett Reese & Paul Wernick want a PG 13 release over the Festive Period because (& get this ) they feel that kids who haven't had a chance to experience Deadpool in the first movie & now 2nd film will do so with the PG13 released versions..  As according to them they have had parents complaining about the fact their kids couldn't watch Deadpool & Deadpool 2 because of its violent nature & all sorts of other BS, but lets remind ourselves of something  & unless I've been spared by Thanos finger click just to get f*cked over or i have been living in an alternate universe then that was the whole FN point of making Deadpool in the first place...  As everyone wanted ti ser proper adult version of these comic book movies with all the violence & foreig left in tact along with some hilarious comedic work by Ryan Reynolds...  If this is true this smacks of total capitalism & the Deadpool franchise will be tainted by such a child friendly version released over Christmas...  I don't honestly know whether to take this news as a wind up or if it is in fact true as Deadpool is due for a Christmas & Festive Release Date & if Ryan Reynolds has OK'D this then he's doing the exact opposite of what & why he fought for nearly 10 years to get this version of Deadpool onto the silver screen & the very reason we all wanted to see & share in that vision also...  I was looking forward to buying Deadpool 2 in the hope of a Director's Cut that added more content not take it out...  We'll just have to wait & see if there's a few different version on the one or multiple discs on its release soon & I honestly do not believe that quite a few parents have stopped there kids from watching R Rated movies my nieces & nephews who have grown up had had kids themselves always asked me to put The Exorcist/Nightmare PnElm Street & many many more brutal adult films because their parents allowed it..  Now I'm the most laid back In/Grandad  you could find but I wasn't letting 7 t o 9 years kids watch those kind of movies while i baby sat them even if my brothers & sisters said "it's ok as we let them watch them at home " as it breeds indifference & before you know it nothing scares them & you have to keep upping the anti as it's all just make believe anyway...  Make believe or not it shouldn't be allowed in movies with games as they become all.ti accustomed to it & want more violence...  It's not as kids don't have a shitload of marvel & DC comics based movies to watch as there's over 20 plus been made in the last 8 or more years - all we adults ask is leave our films alone & don't make them diluted for kids to see unless the R Rated version is on a completely different disc, as that's the only way I see both age groups being happy about this...  I mean seriously you don't hear parents complain & ask for the New Halloween or The Conjuring/Insidious being watered down so kids can watch them as they are meant for adults & just because Deadpool like Logan was aimed purely at the adult audience's it doesn't mean they should be diluted because they have a comic book character in them...  If this story is100% true then hopefully there is a few separate versions, one for adults & one for kids on the DVD/Blu Ray release because that PG 13 Rated movie will not make as much money & if these writers are doing it for the money (which is my bet) it makes sense to cover all angles & deliver 2 different version on on overall package or it will not sell as we as expected...   Deadpool took nearly 10 years to come to the big screen as Reynolds & the writers were shown the door every time unless the toned the film down because it was too violent & had content regarding sexual & other political or just piss taking content within this film that actually made this movie sell as wrll as I t did because comic book & non comic book fans wanted to see how this played out also & it took independent funding & the ongoing tweeking of cgi effects that could be done within their budget & the very first fight scene shoot at about 70% as close to the original is what secured them the finances to to go ahead & make the first Deadpool movie...
